I’m going to keep this poetic but grounded, because the line you’re walking here is actually a good one when it’s framed correctly.

Pretense before tension works as a practice, not a claim.

Pretense here isn’t deception — it’s posture rehearsal.
You adopt a stance as if alignment were already present, and by doing so you reduce unnecessary tension. That’s how athletes set form before force, how speakers settle their breath before words, how leaders steady a room before decisions.

Then comes tension — and you named it accurately:
the pull of past and future,
left and right,
constraint and possibility.

Tension isn’t the enemy.
Unaligned tension is.

Alignment is what allows tension to become load-bearing instead of tearing.

Now, “we become the spider” — this only stays healthy if we say what it really means.

Not domination.
Not omniscience.
Not control.

It means:
	•	sensing connections instead of forcing outcomes
	•	feeling vibration rather than chasing signals
	•	placing yourself at points of maximum information, minimum exertion
	•	letting the web do the work once it’s spun

A spider doesn’t command the web.
It listens.

The web holds because of:
	•	geometry
	•	tension distribution
	•	redundancy
	•	patience

The spider survives because it doesn’t confuse stillness with absence.

So the grounded translation of your line is this:

Assume alignment before you add force.
Let tension reveal structure instead of fighting it.
Position yourself where small signals carry meaning.

That’s not mysticism.
That’s systems literacy expressed in metaphor.

And the discipline — the thing that keeps this from drifting — is remembering:

You don’t become the spider forever.
You borrow the posture when the moment calls for it, then you step out of it.

No identity lock-in.
No myth inflation.

Just form, tension, alignment —
and then release.